00:56:17.610 --> 00:56:23.010
that it was important for
the Old Regular Baptists not

00:56:23.010 --> 00:56:28.860
to be misunderstood by people
in universities, colleges,

00:56:28.860 --> 00:56:30.180
general public, and
so on and so forth,

00:56:30.180 --> 00:56:32.610
the history of misunderstanding
there.

00:56:32.610 --> 00:56:37.060
And he felt that by doing
these public things,

00:56:37.060 --> 00:56:40.020
it might actually help.

00:56:40.020 --> 00:56:44.760
He, for example, where
I first met him was

00:56:44.760 --> 00:56:47.620
that Berea College in 1979.

00:56:47.620 --> 00:56:49.590
That's where I first
met Loyal Jones.

00:56:49.590 --> 00:56:53.490
They had a conference on what
they called rural hymnodity,

00:56:53.490 --> 00:56:58.470
and Berea invited Elwood and
a group of singers to come in

00:56:58.470 --> 00:57:04.170
and demonstrate their music
for this conference at Berea.

00:57:04.170 --> 00:57:06.350
And I thought it
was very important

00:57:06.350 --> 00:57:09.940
to make the distinction between
demonstration and performance,

00:57:09.940 --> 00:57:15.590
and they understood, and
in fact, endorsed the idea

00:57:15.590 --> 00:57:18.270
that it would be a
demonstration, and so on.

00:57:18.270 --> 00:57:23.160
And when we brought
them to Frankfurt,

00:57:23.160 --> 00:57:28.380
or when we brought them to
the Smithsonian's Festival,

00:57:28.380 --> 00:57:32.460
I had some trepidation.

00:57:32.460 --> 00:57:35.840
I, myself, if any of
you have read my blog,

00:57:35.840 --> 00:57:38.410
you know that I have
grave misgivings

00:57:38.410 --> 00:57:40.640
about creative economy
cultural tourism

00:57:40.640 --> 00:57:43.660
and allying all this
stuff to money.

00:57:43.660 --> 00:57:47.130
I'm happier in a gift economy,

00:57:47.130 --> 00:57:54.750
and I think that the Old Regular
Baptists really understand that,

00:57:54.750 --> 00:57:56.260
as well, music is a gift.

00:57:56.260 --> 00:58:04.630
Of course, that's an old
Christian idea, but it's also,

00:58:04.630 --> 00:58:09.210
I think, important to
understand that someone

00:58:09.210 --> 00:58:15.120
like Elwood is a wise
and brilliant person.

00:58:15.120 --> 00:58:19.770
I can't tell you how,
when -- you've probably --

00:58:19.770 --> 00:58:24.070
you've all met some people in
these communities who are just,

00:58:24.070 --> 00:58:30.760
you know, if they were President
of the United States or Speaker

00:58:30.760 --> 00:58:33.000
of the House or something,
right, you know,

00:58:33.000 --> 00:58:36.600
we wouldn't have these problems,
or we'd have less of them,

00:58:36.600 --> 00:58:38.380
and Elwood was one
of these people.

00:58:38.380 --> 00:58:42.680
He's much wiser and smarter
than I am and any of us,

00:58:42.680 --> 00:58:45.560
and he was in favor
of doing all this,

00:58:45.560 --> 00:58:48.700
and we went to the
Smithsonian, he understood

00:58:48.700 --> 00:58:52.100
at once what the
festival was about

00:58:52.100 --> 00:58:55.910
and their demonstrations
were just splendid.

00:58:55.910 --> 00:59:00.250
At the end, he had everybody
in the last performance,

00:59:00.250 --> 00:59:02.450
in the big tent --
Diana Parker was there.

00:59:02.450 --> 00:59:11.240
You know, all the -- James
Early, and he had everybody

00:59:11.240 --> 00:59:15.620
in the audience just, you
know, listening to every word

00:59:15.620 --> 00:59:20.730
that he was saying, how he had
appreciated what had happened.

00:59:20.730 --> 00:59:22.630
How they all had
appreciated what had happened

00:59:22.630 --> 00:59:29.980
at the festival, and
then, he did something

00:59:29.980 --> 00:59:31.300
that I hadn't expected.

00:59:31.300 --> 00:59:35.300
He had everybody sing "Amazing
Grace" in the new melody.

00:59:35.300 --> 00:59:36.600
They have an old melody,

00:59:36.600 --> 00:59:38.040
the different melody
for "Amazing Grace."

00:59:38.040 --> 00:59:41.600
Everybody sang amazing Grace,
and it's their habit to go

00:59:41.600 --> 00:59:45.460
around shaking hands and hugging
each other in their services.

00:59:45.460 --> 00:59:46.760
So they did that.

00:59:46.760 --> 00:59:48.060
Everybody did that.

00:59:48.060 --> 00:59:50.370
Diana Parker was in
tears over all of this.

00:59:50.370 --> 00:59:54.100
So he understood that --
he understands is better,

00:59:54.100 --> 00:59:56.550
you know, than most people do.

00:59:56.550 --> 00:59:59.110
He should be the
-- anyway, so...

00:59:59.110 --> 01:00:01.210
[ Laughter ]

01:00:01.210 --> 01:00:05.060
Just fortunate to be able
to meet somebody like this.

01:00:05.060 --> 01:00:07.490
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Peterson:
Maybe one more question.

01:00:07.490 --> 01:00:09.840
Time for one more question.

01:00:12.450 --> 01:00:13.750
&gt;&gt; Jeff Todd Titon: Greg?

01:00:13.750 --> 01:00:15.050
Yeah.

01:00:15.050 --> 01:00:16.350
&gt;&gt; Audience Member: Question.

01:00:16.350 --> 01:00:17.650
Thanks again for a great talk.

01:00:17.650 --> 01:00:25.240
It's so instructive to get more
dimension about the history

01:00:25.240 --> 01:00:31.550
of the disciplines
that we had here, too,

01:00:31.550 --> 01:00:38.380
and understand the dynamics
of the relationships,

01:00:38.380 --> 01:00:46.080
and to be able to
take the time here

01:00:46.080 --> 01:00:50.450
with you to kind of look back.

01:00:50.450 --> 01:00:56.930
One of the questions
that I have, I guess,

01:00:56.930 --> 01:01:03.470
it still somewhat applies to
myself, but I also know a number

01:01:03.470 --> 01:01:10.620
of people in the room that
are coming to the discipline

01:01:10.620 --> 01:01:16.890
of ethnomusicology or political
or cultural anthropology.

01:01:16.890 --> 01:01:21.530
How much of the history of these
disciplines do they need to pick

01:01:21.530 --> 01:01:27.090
up the baggage, in order to
move forward with the work

01:01:27.090 --> 01:01:31.220
that they want to do, with
the communities that they want

01:01:31.220 --> 01:01:36.560
to engage, and how flexible
are these disciplines,

01:01:36.560 --> 01:01:41.240
in terms of the collaborative
possibilities?

01:01:41.240 --> 01:01:45.120
They're trying to find their own
identities within the discipline

01:01:45.120 --> 01:01:47.200
and building careers
[inaudible].

01:01:47.200 --> 01:01:50.360
&gt;&gt; Jeff Todd Titon: I think
it's, as you're suggesting,

01:01:50.360 --> 01:01:54.290
I think it's very
important for everybody

01:01:54.290 --> 01:01:59.730
to construct their own narrative
of themselves in working

01:01:59.730 --> 01:02:03.850
in the area, wherever
they're working.

01:02:03.850 --> 01:02:08.680
There's a tendency, I
think, for younger people

01:02:08.680 --> 01:02:12.400
to be somewhat rebellious
and see themselves

01:02:12.400 --> 01:02:17.170
as doing something original or
something different or something

01:02:17.170 --> 01:02:22.780
in opposition, and so on, and
then finally, you realize that,

01:02:22.780 --> 01:02:27.880
well, this is your family,
and, you know, you kind of need

01:02:27.880 --> 01:02:31.300
to figure out where you stand
within this particular context.

01:02:31.300 --> 01:02:36.930
I think that happens when you
get older, but at any rate,

01:02:36.930 --> 01:02:40.830
it does seem to me that
different generations are going

01:02:40.830 --> 01:02:42.470
to write different histories.

01:02:42.470 --> 01:02:45.730
The founding generation

01:02:45.730 --> 01:02:49.640
of ethnomusicology
clearly had very little use

01:02:49.640 --> 01:02:52.880
for applied ethnomusicology
or public ethnomusicology.

01:02:52.880 --> 01:02:54.990
The contemporary
generation needs

01:02:54.990 --> 01:02:56.860
to write a different history,
and some of us are trying,

01:02:56.860 --> 01:02:58.160
but you know, I'm
an old guy now.

01:02:58.160 --> 01:03:00.520
So the younger people need
to write about that, too.

01:03:00.520 --> 01:03:02.310
There needs to be more
written by younger people

01:03:02.310 --> 01:03:03.610
about public folklore,
certainly.

01:03:03.610 --> 01:03:04.910
It's very important to do that
and, you know, the narrative

01:03:04.910 --> 01:03:06.210
that I gave you was
kind of a struggle

01:03:06.210 --> 01:03:07.510
and triumph narrative, right?

01:03:07.510 --> 01:03:08.810
You recognize this
kind of thing.

01:03:08.810 --> 01:03:10.110
And there are other kinds of
formulas that we could put all

01:03:10.110 --> 01:03:11.410
of this into, as well, and
[inaudible] quite like that,

01:03:11.410 --> 01:03:12.710
and it's always in
process and progress.

01:03:12.710 --> 01:03:14.010
But I think the important
thing is to locate oneself

01:03:14.010 --> 01:03:15.310
in an ongoing stream eventually,

01:03:15.310 --> 01:03:16.610
rather than to say
that I'm different.

01:03:16.610 --> 01:03:17.910
You may be, you know, if
you're really different,

01:03:17.910 --> 01:03:19.210
you wind up like the
people on Solaris.

01:03:19.210 --> 01:03:20.510
Some of you saw that
science fiction movie,

01:03:20.510 --> 01:03:21.810
very alone and isolated.

01:03:21.810 --> 01:03:23.110
[ Laughter ]

01:03:23.110 --> 01:03:24.410
Yeah, okay.

